  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT73-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">pakaṟkuṟi maṟuttu iravukkuṟi nērntu atuvu maṟuttamai paṭat talaimakaṭkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante to HER after having refused a day tryst, [but] granted a night tryst, in order to refuse also the latter.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT73">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                makiḻnaṉ mārpē veyyai yāṉī</l>
<l>                yaḻiyal vāḻi tōḻi naṉṉa</l>
<l>                ṉaṟumā koṉṟu nāṭṭiṟ pōkiya</l>
<l>                voṉṟumoḻik kōcar pōla</l>
<l>                vaṉkaṭ cūḻcciyum vēṇṭumāṟ ciṟitē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Just for the delightful man's(?) chest you are aglow,</l>
          <l>don't worry, oh friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent">as with the Kōcars of one counsel</l>
          <l rend="indent">who went to Naṉṉaṉ's land [and] felled [his] fragrant Mango tree<note place="foot">The legend (attested only in KT 292) says that <term xml:lang="ta">Naṉṉaṉ</term> in rage had a girl killed who had by accident eaten a mango fruit of his tutelary tree, that had fallen into the river. Indignant about this disgraceful deed (the killing of a woman), his enemies, the <term xml:lang="ta">Kōcars</term>, decided to destroy him: they cut down the tree of the defeated king. The only further textual reference is an allusion in PN 151.</note></l>
          <l>what is necessary, too, is a little crafty<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vaṉkaṇ</term> or <term xml:lang="ta">vaṉ kaṇ</term> "strong eye" = "sharp-eyed" planning (cf. also KT 274.4).</note> planning.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
